Intent and implementation should be separated.

Intent is a nicer material to work with than implementation. It is easier to understand, easier to expand, easier to change, and easier to discard.

Intent is written directly as code. Implementation is derived from it.

An idea is stable when different people understand it the same way. A specification is stable when different implementations preserve the same meaning.

Humans and machines both reason better about complete things.

Instead of complaining about syntax, the compiler should complain about missing ideas or unclear meaning.

Software is a collaboration between the programmer and their compiler.

Programming is a communication of intent. 
